{{Infobox storm | name = 2012 storm in Uruguay | image = | caption = | formed = September 18, 2012 | dissipated = September 19, 2012 | lowest pressure = 992 | highest winds = 172 | countries affected = Southern [[Uruguay]] | damages = | casualties = 3 total }}
In 2012, a strong [[storm]] swept across southern [[Uruguay]] from 18 to 19 September.<ref name="tormenta"/>
==Facts== The main area affected were the departments on the [[Río de la Plata|River Plate]] and [[Atlantic]] coasts: Colonia, San José, Montevideo, Canelones, Maldonado, Rocha.<ref name="tormenta"/>
The strongest winds were in Punta del Este (172&nbsp;km/h), Montevideo (122&nbsp;km/h), Laguna del Sauce (120&nbsp;km/h), Colonia (103&nbsp;km/h), San José (102&nbsp;km/h), Melo (98&nbsp;km/h), Tacuarembó (87&nbsp;km/h), Rivera (83&nbsp;km/h).<ref name="tormenta"/>
The government was forced to close public buildings, suspend transport and recommend residents in the capital Montevideo and other locations along the coast to remain at home. Luckily enough, it was the week of spring holidays, so children did not have to attend school.<ref name="mercopress">{{cite web|url=http://en.mercopress.com/2012/09/20/spring-cyclone-paralyzes-uruguay-s-capital-as-residents-are-told-to-stay-at-home|title=Spring cyclone paralyzes Uruguay’s capital |date=20 Sep 2012|publisher=MercoPress}}</ref>
==Aftermath== [[Meteorologist]]s considered this to be an [[extratropical cyclone]].<ref name="tormenta">{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.elobservador.com.uy/noticia/232955/tres-muertos-por-el-temporal/|title=3 people dead in the storm|date=20 Sep 2012|accessdate=|publisher=[[El Observador (Uruguay)|El Observador]]|language=Spanish}}</ref>
General comment was that his cyclone was less severe than the [[2005 Uruguay storm|2005 storm]].<ref name="2005-2012">{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.elobservador.com.uy/noticia/232947/el-ciclon-extratropical-de-2005-fue-mas-profundo-que-el-de-ayer/ |title=2005 cyclone much worse than 2012|date=20 Sep 2012|accessdate=|publisher=El Observador|language=Spanish}}</ref>
Three people were reported dead in San José, due to a flood.<ref name="tormenta"/>
This storm is part of a regional phenomenon covering also Argentina, Paraguay, and Bolivia, where other people were reported dead as well.<ref name="regional">{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.elpais.com.uy/12/09/20/ultmo_664902.asp |title=Southern Cone panics with the cyclone |date=20 Sep 2012|accessdate=|publisher=EL PAIS|language=Spanish}}</ref>
