{{Refimprove|date=October 2010}} {{Infobox military conflict |conflict=Battle of Yanling |partof= |image= |caption= |date= 575 BC |place=[[Yanling County, Henan|Yanling]], Henan |casus= |territory= |result=Jin victory |combatant1=Chu |combatant2=Jin |commander1=[[King Gong of Chu]] |commander2=[[Duke Li of Jin]] |strength1=Unknown |strength2=Unknown |casualties1=Unknown |casualties2=Unknown }} The '''Battle of Yanling''' ({{zh|t=鄢陵之戰}}) was fought in 575 BC between the states of [[Chu (state)|Chu]] and [[Jin (Chinese state)|Jin]] at [[Yanling County, Henan|Yanling]] during the [[Spring and Autumn period]] of ancient China. On the Jin side, [[Xi Qi]] (郤錡) commanded the right wing whilst [[Luan Shu]] (欒書) commanded the center with [[Han Jue]] (韓厥) on the left . Prior to the battle, Shi Xie wanted to avoid battle on the basis that external enemies are necessary for internal peace. The Chu army had the numerical advantage but with the exception of the King's personal guard, it was in poor condition. The Chu army was also commanded by [[Zifan]] (子反) and [[Zichong]] (子重), who hated each other. Following Luan Shu's advice, the Jin army took a defensive posture instead of going on the offensive. By dawn the Jin armies were deployed behind a marsh and ditch, which impeded Chu troops. Fen Huang, a Jin officer, pointed out that the best Chu troops in the center was bogged down by the marsh, leaving the flanks to be held only by badly disciplined 'wild tribes of the south'. Jin [[Chariot (Ancient China)|chariot]]s then charged both Chu flanks, scattering the enemy. They then proceeded to attack the center, which contained the Chu King commanding his troops. Although the Chu King's life was endangered a couple of times, Jin officers let him escape as a sign of respect. However, he was wounded by an arrow and his army was driven back.<ref>Imperial Chinese Military History: 8000 BC –1912 AD, Marvin C Whiting(Writers Club Press), pp 44–45</ref> <ref name="zuozhuan">{{cite web |url=https://sites.google.com/site/dalriadabooks/five-classics/tso-chuan/chinese-english-zuo-zhuan/book-viii-duke-cheng/xvi-sixteenth-year |title=春秋左传 (The Commentary of Zuo) |work=[[The Spring and Autumn]] |author=[[Zuo Qiuming]] |language=Chinese, English |accessdate=26 February 2016}}</ref>
