The conference provoked criticism.<ref>[[Amir Taheri]]. ''The Persian Night: Iran Under the Khomeinist Revolution'', Encounter Books, 2010, p. 143.</ref> The [[Holy See|Vatican]] condemned it, the [[Executive Office of the President|US administration]] of President [[George W. Bush]] called it an "affront to the entire civilized world," and British Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]] described it as "shocking beyond belief."<ref name=Guttenplan>{{cite web|url=http://commentisfree.guardian.co.uk/dd_guttenplan/2006/12/the_holocaust_deniers_ball.html|title=Comment is free - The Guardian|publisher=}}</ref> Holocaust historians attending a separate conference in [[Berlin]] organized in protest against the Iranian one called it "an attempt to cloak [[anti-Semitism]] in scholarly language."<ref name=Barnard>{{cite web|url=http://www.boston.com/news/world/articles/2006/12/12/conference_in_iran_on_holocaust_begins/|title=Conference in Iran on Holocaust begins|work=Boston.com}}</ref>

==Goals==
According to the Iranian Foreign Ministry, the conference would not aim to deny or prove [[the Holocaust]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/NR/exeres/6490BD25-3FFA-4E7D-9D1F-D3A23F7E84DF.htm|title=Iran hosts Holocaust conference (Al Jazeera)|accessdate=2006-12-13}}</ref> but to create opportunities "for suitable scientific research so that the hidden and unhidden angles of this most important political issue of the 20th century becomes more transparent." The event was organized by the ministry's Institute for Political & International Studies (IPIS).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ipis.ir/english/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-05-28 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070128081129/http://www.ipis.ir/English/ |archivedate=2007-01-28 |df= }}</ref>

The goal of the conference was to discuss the reality of the [[Nazism|Nazis]]' extermination of [[Jew]]s during [[World War II]].<ref name=BBC/> The [[Foreign Minister of Iran]] and other officials stated that the conference was meant to "create an opportunity for thinkers who cannot express their views freely in Europe about the Holocaust".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/0,1518,453691,00.html |title=Berlin Counters Holocaust Conference: "This Is What Happened" - SPIEGEL ONLINE |publisher=Spiegel.de |date=2006-12-11 |accessdate=2013-10-26}}</ref>

According to the Iranian Foreign Minister: "If the official version of the Holocaust is thrown into doubt, then the identity and nature of Israel will be thrown into doubt. And if, during this review, it is proved that the Holocaust was a historical reality, then what is the reason for the Palestinians having to pay the cost of the Nazis' crimes?"<ref name=lefkovits/>

==Attendees==
There were 67 attendees from 30 countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20061214/OPINION/612140314|title=Holocaust deniers spread fiction in Iran|work=recordonline.com}}</ref><ref name=fathi>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/11/world/middleeast/11cnd-iran.html|title=Holocaust Deniers and Skeptics Gather in Iran|first=Nazila|last=Fathi|work=New York Times|date=2006-12-11|accessdate=2006-12-12}}</ref>

<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Jews at 2006 Iran Holocaust conference.jpg|right|thumb|250px|{{ifdc|Jews at 2006 Iran Holocaust conference.jpg|log=2009 December 22}} Members of the anti-Zionist [[Jews|Jewish]] organisation [[Neturei Karta]] at the conference.]] -->
American [[David Duke]], a former [[Louisiana State Legislature|Louisiana State Representative]] and one-time [[Ku Klux Klan]] leader, attended the conference. French writer Georges Thiel, who had been convicted under [[Holocaust denial laws in France]], attended, as did [[Gerald Fredrick Töben|Fredrick Töben]] of Australia who had been imprisoned in Germany for three months in 1999 for Holocaust denial.<ref name=lefkovits>
{{cite web
 |url        = http://fr.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1164881868416&pagename=JPost/JPArticle/ShowFull
 |title      = Israel slams Iran Holocaust conference
 |first      = Etgar
 |last       = Lefkovits
 |publisher  = Jerusalem Post
 |date       = 2006-12-11
 |accessdate = 2006-12-12
}}{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=reuters/> [[Robert Faurisson]], a convicted Holocaust denier from France also attended,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nizkor.org/ftp.cgi/people/f/ftp.py?people/f//faurisson.robert/holocaust-denial-today| title=Nizkor.org|accessdate=2006-12-13}}</ref> as well as [[Ahmed Rami (writer)|Ahmed Rami]], a [[Sweden|Swedish]]-[[Morocco|Moroccan]] [[Holocaust denier]] who was imprisoned in Sweden for [[incitement to ethnic or racial hatred|inciting racial hatred]].<ref name=rami>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsfront.info/txt/EEyuZFuZpZEtFUchJn.shtml |title=Föreläsning i Stockholm om judefrågan |language=Swedish |publisher=[[National Socialist Front]] |date=2006-11-25 |accessdate=2006-12-13 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080709044353/http://www.nsfront.info/txt/EEyuZFuZpZEtFUchJn.shtml |archivedate=2008-07-09 |df= }}</ref> German psychologist and [[National Democratic Party of Germany]] (NPD) functionary Bendikt Frings was invited by Iranian Deputy Minister of Islamic Guidance [[Mohammad Ali Ramin]]; Frings said that he had waited for such a conference "all my childhood".<ref>
{{cite news| url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2006-12-12/news/17323179_1_holocaust-deniers-nazi-death-machine-europe-s-jews | work=[[The San Francisco Chronicle]] | first=Nazila | last=Fathi | title=Letters To The Editor | date=2006-12-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/tehranbureau/2010/11/the-political-craft-of-mahmoud-ahmadinejad-part-ii-the-great-balancing-act.html |title=The Political Craft of Mahmoud Ahmadinejad &#124; Part 2: The Great Balancing Act - Tehran Bureau|publisher=[[PBS Frontline]] |date=2010-11-29 |accessdate=2013-10-26}}</ref> The NPD is widely considered the most significant German Neo-Nazi party.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thelocal.de/politics/20080609-12381.html |title=Neo-Nazi NPD party takes hold in municipal vote in Saxony |publisher=[[The Local]] |date=9 Jun 2008 |accessdate=2013-10-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.austriantimes.at/index.php?id=12379|title=Austrian Times - News - Finanzen und Wirtschaft in Österreich|website=www.austriantimes.at|access-date=2011-05-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531201818/http://www.austriantimes.at/index.php?id=12379|archive-date=2011-05-31|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>

[[Michèle Renouf]], an Australian-born British defender of Holocaust denial author [[David Irving]] also attended. At the conference, Renouf claimed that the "terrible things" that happened to the Jews in World War II were brought upon by Jewish leaders.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2006/dec/12/iran.israel | location=London | work=[[The Guardian]] | first=Robert | last=Tait | title=Holocaust deniers gather in Iran for 'scientific' conference | date=2006-12-12}}</ref>

Among the participants at the conference were six members of the [[anti-Zionist]] [[Jews|Jewish]] organisation [[Neturei Karta]], including Aharon Cohen<ref name=spillius>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2006/12/12/wiran12.xml|title=Iran stirs up hatred with Holocaust conference|first=Alex|last=Spillius|date=2006-12-12|accessdate=2006-12-12 | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref><ref name=cohen>{{cite web|url=http://www.nkusa.org/activities/Speeches/2006Iran-ACohen.cfm|title=Orthodox Jewish Attitude to the 'Holocaust'|first=Aharon|last=Cohen|publisher=Neturei Karta USA|date=2006-12-12|accessdate=2006-12-12}}</ref> who said he had come to the conference to put the [[Orthodox Jewish]] viewpoint across. Cohen also said that while the Holocaust indisputably happened, "in no way can it be used as a justification for perpetrating unjust acts against the [[Palestinians]]."<ref name=BBC/>

[[Shiraz Dossa]], a professor of Political Science at [[St. Francis Xavier University]] in [[Nova Scotia]], [[Canada]],  presented a paper at the conference and was roundly vilified for his participation by the Canadian media and his university.<ref name=CBC1>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2006/12/13/professor-holocaust061213.html|title=Canadian prof's presence at Iran forum 'abhorrent': university|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|date=December 13, 2006}}</ref>

{{Interlanguage link multi|Jan Bernhoff|sv}}, a computer teacher from Sweden, gave a presentation claiming that 300,000 Jews had been killed as opposed to six million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thelocal.se/5797/20061214/ |title=Swedish teacher at Holocaust denial conference - The Local |publisher=Thelocal.se |date= |accessdate=2013-10-26}}</ref>

[[France|French]] Holocaust denier [[Roger Garaudy]] was unable to attend the conference for health reasons. However, he reportedly sent a videotaped message supporting [[Iranian President]] [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]]'s view that Israel should cease to exist.<ref name=bookreview>{{cite web |url=http://www.asharq-e.com/news.asp?section=8&id=8605 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-04-23 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090224180036/http://asharq-e.com/news.asp?section=8 |archivedate=2009-02-24 |df= }}</ref>

===Denied permission===
[[Israeli Arab]] lawyer [[Khaled Kasab Mahameed]] was denied permission to attend the conference by Iran after it was discovered that he holds [[Israeli citizenship]]. He had been previously invited to attend by the Iranian government;<ref name=lefkovits2>{{cite web|url=http://fr.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1164881865648&pagename=JPost/JPArticle/ShowFull|title=Iran bars Israeli Arab from Shoah forum|first=Etgar|last=Lefkovits|publisher=Jerusalem Post|date=2006-12-10|accessdate=2006-12-12}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> however Iran does not grant [[visa (document)|visas]] to Israelis. According to ''[[Ha'aretz]]'', Mahameed intended "to tell the conference that the Holocaust did happen and that Iranian President Mahmoud Ahmadinejad's position of Holocaust denial is wrong". He stated:

<blockquote>Everything that happened must be internalized and the facts must not be denied... It is the obligation of all Arabs and all Muslims to understand the significance of the Holocaust. If their goal is to understand their adversary, they must understand the Holocaust... The ''[[1948 Palestinian exodus|naqba]]'' [disaster] the Palestinians experienced in 1948 is small compared to the Holocaust, but the political implications of the Holocaust have made its terrors a burden on the Palestinian people alone... The Holocaust has all the reasons for the creation of the Arab-Israeli conflict, but also has potential to bring peace."<ref name=Stern>{{cite web|url=http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/789142.html|title=Founder of Holocaust museum in Nazareth invited to Tehran|first=Yoav|last=Stern|publisher=[[Haaretz]]|date=2006-11-17|accessdate=2006-12-12}}</ref></blockquote>

==Conference events==
The Iranian President [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] was quoted as saying: "The Zionist regime will be wiped out soon the same way the Soviet Union was, and humanity will achieve freedom [and] elections should be held among Jews, Christians and Muslims so the population of Palestine can select their government and destiny for themselves in a democratic manner."<ref name=JerusalemPost12Dec06>http://www.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?c=JPArticle&cid=1164881878838&pagename=JPost%2FJPArticle%2FshowFull</ref>

Papers delivered by participants from countries ranging from Austria to Indonesia included "A Challenge to the Official Holocaust Story," and "Holocaust, the Achilles Heel of a Primordial Jewish Trojan."<ref name=METimes>{{cite web|url=http://www.metimes.com/storyview.php?StoryID=20061212-105225-2773r|title=Iran defiant as anger mounts over Holocaust forum|date=2006-12-12|accessdate=2006-12-15}}</ref>

[[David Duke]] gave a speech in which he said: "In Europe you can freely question, ridicule and deny [[Jesus|Jesus Christ]]. The same is true for the prophet [[Muhammad]], and nothing will happen to you. But offer a single question of the smallest part of the Holocaust and you face prison."<ref name=lefkovits/>

[[Frederick Töben]] told the conference: "Minds are being switched off to the Holocaust dogma as it is being sold as a historical fact and yet we are not able to question it. This is mental rape."<ref name=theodoulou>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,20867,20919335-12332,00.html|title=Leader gets lesson on free speech at Iran uni|first=Michael|last=Theodoulou|publisher=The Australian|date=2006-12-13|accessdate=2006-12-12}}</ref>

Rabbi Aharon Cohen told the conference: "There is no doubt whatsoever, that during World War II there developed a terrible and catastrophic policy and action of [[genocide]] perpetrated by [[Nazi Germany]] against the Jewish people, confirmed by innumerable eyewitness survivors and fully documented again and again...The figure of six million is regularly quoted. One may wish to dispute this actual figure, but the crime was just as dreadful whether the millions of victims numbered six million, five million or four million. The method of murder is also irrelevant, whether it was by [[gas chamber]], firing squads or whatever. The evil was the same. It would be a terrible affront to the memory of those who perished to belittle the guilt of the crime in any way.<ref name=cohen/>

[[Richard Krege]] maintained his suggestion of diesel exhaust gas chambers to be an "outright lie," and showed a model of the [[Treblinka extermination camp]] to illustrate this.<ref name=METimes/> He claimed that up to 10,000 people died in the camp, but of disease, instead of planned extermination.<ref name=METimes/> He said, "There is no scientific proof to show that this place was an extermination camp. All that exists are the words of some people."<ref name=METimes/>

===Conclusions===
According to ''[[IRNA]]'', the conference participants agreed to start a world foundation for Holocaust studies with [[Mohammad-Ali Ramin]] as its Secretary General. The stated purpose of the foundation was to "find out the truth about holocaust."  More immediate tasks included preparing for the next Holocaust conference and composing the foundation's letter of association. The main office would initially be located in Tehran, though Ramin said it will eventually move to [[Berlin]], "once proper grounds are prepared".<ref>{{cite web|title=World foundation for holocaust studies set up in Tehran |url=http://www.irna.ir/en/news/view/line-22/0612141586200734.htm |accessdate=2006-12-16 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930230003/http://www.irna.ir/en/news/view/line-22/0612141586200734.htm |archivedate=September 30, 2007 }}</ref>

==Reactions==

===Iran===
Iran's sole Jewish member of parliament [[Maurice Motamed]] said: "Holding this conference after having a [[International Holocaust Cartoon Competition|competition of cartoons about the Holocaust]] has put a lot of pressure on Jews all over the world;"<ref name=BBC/> and that "The conference has upset Iran's 25,000-strong Jewish community."<ref name=reuters>{{cite news|url=http://today.reuters.com/news/articlenews.aspx?type=worldNews&storyID=2006-12-11T085515Z_01_L11639597_RTRUKOC_0_US-IRAN-HOLOCAUST.xml&WTmodLoc=NewsHome-C3-worldNews-3|title=Iran opens conference questioning the Holocaust|author= Hafezi, Parisa|publisher=Reuters|date=2006-11-12|accessdate=2006-12-13}}</ref>

Though reformist demonstrations had been rare since Ahmadinejad took office, a few dozen students burnt pictures of him and chanted "death to the dictator" as Ahmadinejad gave a speech at [[Amirkabir University of Technology]] in Tehran on 12 December 2006.<ref name=theodoulou/> One student activist said the protest was against the "shameful" Holocaust conference, and added that Ahmadinejad had "brought to our country Nazis and racists from around the world."<ref name="theodoulou"/> Ahmadinejad responded by saying: "Everyone should know that Ahmadinejad is prepared to be burnt in the path of true freedom, independence and justice."<ref name=theodoulou/>

However, Ali Akbar Mohtashamipour, Secretary-General of the International Congress to Support the Palestinian Intifada, expressed support for the conference, saying that the "Western and Zionist media have always been aggrandizing the dimensions of the reality of Holocaust, mixing a bit of truth with a lot of lies".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldpoliticsreview.com/trend-lines/408/irans-appalling-holocaust-conference|title=Iran's Appalling Holocaust Conference|author=The Editors|publisher=}}</ref>

===International===
;Supranational bodies
{{AS}}
*{{flagicon|United Nations}} [[United Nations]] [[Secretary General]] [[Ban Ki-moon]]  said "Denying historical facts, especially on such an important subject as the Holocaust, is just not acceptable. Nor is it acceptable to call for the elimination of any State or people. I would like to see this fundamental principle respected both in rhetoric and in practice by all the members of the international community.  United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan himself visited Iran and had a series of dialogues with the Iranian leadership and other senior-level people. Wherever and when, and if the situation requires me to do, I am also prepared to engage in dialogue with the Iranian leadership."<ref>{{cite web|title=Tehran Conference-public consequences |url=http://www.adelaideinstitute.org/2006December/contents_prog_consequences1.htm |date=2006-12-14 |accessdate=2006-12-16 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070109043348/http://www.adelaideinstitute.org/2006December/contents_prog_consequences1.htm |archivedate=2007-01-09 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>
*During a visit to Iran in September 2006, then [[United Nations]] [[Secretary General]] [[Kofi Annan]] also criticized this conference, saying "I think the tragedy of the Holocaust is an undeniable historical fact and we should really accept that fact and teach people what happened in World War II and ensure it is never repeated."<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/story/2006/09/03/annan-iran.html | work=[[CBC News]] | title=Iranian PM snubs Annan over nuclear program | date=2006-09-03}}</ref>

;States
* {{flag|Belgium}} - Foreign Minister [[Karel De Gucht]] said he "condemned the revisionistic and negationistic expressions (of Iran) and the repeated questioning of the [[right to exist]] for the state of Israel."<ref name=nieuwsbank>{{cite web|url=http://www.nieuwsbank.nl/inp/2006/12/13/F082.htm|title=Perscommunication Federal Government of Belgium|publisher=Federal Government of Belgium|date=2006-12-12|accessdate=2006-12-12}}</ref>
* {{flag|Canada}} - Minister of Foreign Affairs [[Peter MacKay]] said that the conference was "an outrage". "It is an insult to Holocaust victims. It is an insult to their descendants. Canada's new government and I am sure many others in this  House (of Commons) and around the globe condemn this conference, just as we have previously condemned the Iranian president's comments about the Holocaust as hateful."<ref name=Hansard>{{cite web|url=http://www2.parl.gc.ca/HousePublications/Publication.aspx?Language=E&Mode=1&Parl=39&Pub=hansard&Ses=1&DocId=2598624&File=0|title=Official Report: Number 096 (Official Version)|publisher=Canadian House of Commons|date=2006-12-12|accessdate=2006-12-13}}</ref>
* {{flag|France}} - Prior to the conference, Foreign Minister [[Philippe Douste-Blazy]] said France would condemn the conference if participants used it for Holocaust denial.<ref name=fathi/> After the conference opened, Douste-Blazy stated to French RTL radio, "I reiterate our utter condemnation of this conference and the revisionist ideas it’s given a platform to."<ref name="ambafrance-uk.org">{{cite web|url=http://www.ambafrance-uk.org/Philippe-Douste-Blazy-condemns,8235 |title=Philippe Douste-Blazy on Holocaust conference and UN Security Council resolution on sanctions - France in the United Kingdom - La France au Royaume-Uni |publisher=Ambafrance-uk.org |date=2006-12-14 |accessdate=2013-10-26}}</ref> He cited this conference as further evidence of Iranian president [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]]'s "shocking" and "unacceptable" statements, and that this conference violated the 2005 United Nations resolution on Holocaust remembrance, which "rejects any denial of the Holocaust as a historic event, either in full or in part."<ref name="ambafrance-uk.org"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfa.gov.il/MFA/Anti-Semitism+and+the+Holocaust/Documents+and+communiques/UN+General+Assembly+unanimously+designates+January+27+as+Holocaust+Remembrance+Day+1-Nov-2005.htm |title=UN General Assembly unanimously designates January 27 as Holocaust Remembrance Day |publisher=Mfa.gov.il |date= |accessdate=2013-10-26}}</ref>
* {{flag|Germany}} - [[Chancellor of Germany (Federal Republic)|Chancellor]] [[Angela Merkel]], after a meeting with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert, said "I would like to make clear that we reject with all our strength the conference taking place in Iran about the supposed nonexistence of the Holocaust."<ref name=JerusalemPost12Dec06/> According to the ''[[New York Times]]'', the "German government summoned the Iranian chargé d’affaires in [[Berlin]] to complain."<ref name=fathi/>
* {{flag|Israel}} - Prime Minister [[Ehud Olmert]] "denounced the conference before embarking on a two-day trip to Germany"<ref name=lefkovits/> calling the gathering "a sick phenomenon that shows the depths of hatred of the [[Islamic fundamentalism|fundamentalist]] Iranian regime."<ref name=BBC>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/6167695.stm|title=Iran defends Holocaust conference|publisher=BBC News|date=2006-12-11|accessdate=2006-12-12}}</ref> [[Tzipi Livni]], the [[Israeli Foreign Minister]], "commented on the Holocaust conference at a [[Knesset]] meeting ... and said, 'I didn’t come to this meeting to argue with the evil one from Tehran and his allies. He can’t erase the pain of the survivors.'"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3338811,00.html|title=Iran conference attendee: Holocaust an enormous lie|work=ynet}}</ref>
* {{flag|Mexico}} - The government issued a letter disapproving of the Conference and its results. In a statement on its website, the Foreign Secretary wrote that: "The government of Mexico, through the office of the Foreign Secretary, agrees with the international disapproval of the Iranian ''Conference on the Holocaust''...and rejects all negation, either partial or total, of the Holocaust as historical fact."(translation)<ref>{{cite web|title=Mexico rejection letter|url=http://www.sre.gob.mx/csocial/comunicados/2006/dicie/b_247.htm}}</ref>
* {{flag|Poland}} - The Ministry of Foreign Affairs said on its website that Poland "expresses its strong disapproval of the conference, which contradicts the idea of the International Day of Commemoration in Memory of the Victims of the Holocaust established by the UN General Assembly, and celebrated on 27 January...Any attempt at contesting this truth arouses serious concern in Poland, where 6 million people were victims of the Nazi genocide".  The Ministry also consigned informational material from the Auschwitz-Birkenau State Museum to Iranian scholars, seeking to "deepen their knowledge" of the Holocaust.<ref>{{cite web|title=Statement of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs concerning the International Conference on the Holocaust, Teheran, 11–12 December 2006|url=http://www.msz.gov.pl/Statement,of,the,Ministry,of,Foreign,Affairs,concerning,the,International,Conference,on,the,Holocaust,,Teheran,,11-12,December,2006,8594.html|
accessdate=2006-12-15}}</ref>

* {{flag|Sweden}} - [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Sweden)|Minister for Foreign Affairs]] [[Carl Bildt]] said: "The Iranian regime's statements about Israel and the questioning of the Holocaust are completely unacceptable, as well as Iran's questioning of the state of Israel's right to exist."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.riksdagen.se/Webbnav/index.aspx?nid=71&dok_id=GU12354 |title=Svar på skriftlig fråga 2006/07:354 |accessdate=2009-02-01 |date=2006-12-20 |publisher=The [[Riksdag]] |language=Swedish |quote=Den iranska regimens uttalanden om Israel och ifrågasättandet av Förintelsen är helt oacceptabla, liksom Irans ifrågasättande av staten Israels rätt att existera.}}</ref>
* {{flag|Switzerland}} - Foreign Ministry spokesman Johann Aeschlimann said that the ministry condemned any querying of the right of Israel to exist, as had once again happened in Tehran, and of the Holocaust. "The [[Shoah]] is a historical fact. It is unacceptable to call this into question."<ref>
{{cite web|url=http://www.swissinfo.org/eng/front/detail/Foreign_ministry_condemns_Iran_conference.html?siteSect=105&sid=7344720&cKey=1165987544000|
title=Foreign ministry condemns Iran conference|publisher=Swissinfo|date=2006-12-12|accessdate=2006-12-15}}</ref>

* {{flag|United Kingdom}} - Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]] denounced the conference as "shocking beyond belief."<ref name="Guttenplan" /> Blair also said that it was "a symbol of [[sectarianism]] and hatred toward people of another religion. I mean, to go and invite the former head of the Ku Klux Klan to a conference in Tehran which disputes the millions of people who died in the Holocaust … what further evidence do you need that this regime is extreme?"<ref name=CBC>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/world/story/2006/12/12/holocaust-iran-061212.html|title=Iran's Holocaust conference 'shocking beyond belief': Blair|publisher=[[CBC News]]|date=2006-12-12|accessdate=2006-12-12}}</ref>
* {{flag|United States}} - The [[U.S. State Department|State Department]] described the Iranian event as "yet another disgraceful act on this particular subject by the regime in Tehran.<ref name=BBC/> It is just flabbergasting that they continue &mdash; that the leadership of that regime continues to deny that six million-plus people were killed in the Holocaust," spokesman [[Sean McCormack]] said.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/r/pa/prs/dpb/2006/77530.htm |title=Daily Press Briefing, December 8, 2006 |accessdate=2006-12-13 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061212215110/http://www.state.gov/r/pa/prs/dpb/2006/77530.htm |archivedate=December 12, 2006 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> The [[White House]] called it an "affront to the entire civilised world."<ref name="Guttenplan"/>

;Religious leaders

*The [[Archbishop of Canterbury]] declared the conference a "disgrace", and called for the Holocaust to be memorialised in order to prevent its denial by future generations.<ref name="wjc">"Dateline World Jewry", April 2007, [[World Jewish Congress]]</ref>
*[[Chief Rabbinate of Israel|Ashkenazi Chief Rabbi of Israel]] [[Yonah Metzger]] called upon Jews worldwide to [[Herem (censure)|shun]] members of Neturei Karta who attended the conference and refuse them entrance to synagogues.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/story/2006/12/14/israel-ban-061214.html|title=Boycott Jews who attended Iran conference, top rabbi urges|publisher=[[CBC news]]|date=2006-12-14|accessdate=2006-12-14}}</ref>

=== Non-governmental ===
Thirty four of the world’s leading policy institutes released a statement on 15 December that they would break off all relations with Iran's [[Institute for Political and International Studies]]. Signatories included the directors of the [[International Institute for Strategic Studies]] in [[London]]; the [[Aspen Institute]] in [[Berlin]]; the [[German Marshall Fund]] in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]]; the Geneva Centre for Security Policy; the Center for International Studies and Research in [[Paris]]; the United States Studies Centre in [[Sydney]], [[Australia]]; and the Center for International Relations in [[Warsaw]].<ref name=bennhold>Bennhold, Katrin. [https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/16/world/middleeast/16institute.html?_r=1&oref=slogin "Ties Cut With Iran Institute Over Holocaust,"] ''The New York Times'', December 16, 2006.</ref> The conference was condemned by the [[Council on American-Islamic Relations|Council on American-Islamic Relations (CAIR)]].<ref>{{cite web|title=CAIR Condemns Iranian Holocaust Denial Conference|url=http://pa.cair.com/pressrelease/20061213/|date=2006-12-13}}</ref>

[[Ayaan Hirsi Ali]] called on Western leaders to wake up to the reality of the situation. She stated "For the majority of Muslims in the world the Holocaust is not a major historical event they deny; they simply do not know because they were never informed. Worse, most of us are groomed to wish for a Holocaust of Jews."<ref name=ayaan>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/0,1518,454926,00.html |title=Hirsi Ali Takes on Tehran: Confronting Holocaust Denial |first=Ayaan |last=Hirsi Ali |publisher=Der Spiegel |date=2006-12-15 |accessdate=2006-12-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061217151811/http://www.spiegel.de/international/0%2C1518%2C454926%2C00.html |archivedate=December 17, 2006 |df= }}</ref> She says that she never learned anything about the Holocaust while she was studying in [[Saudi Arabia]] and [[Kenya]]. She called for action from charities: "Western and Christian charities in the third world should take it upon themselves to inform Muslims and non-Muslims alike, in the areas where they are active, about the Holocaust."<ref name=ayaan/>

A number of Arab journalists in Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, and the United Kingdom have criticized this conference, arguing that it included unqualified non-historian speakers, spread the hate and propaganda of an extremist Iranian government, defended the heinous crimes of the Nazis, damaged Iran diplomatically at a time when its foreign relations were difficult, and reflected a lack of human and cultural sensitivity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.memri.org/report/en/0/0/0/0/0/118/2010.htm |title=Criticism of Tehran Holocaust Denial Conference in Arab and Iranian Media |publisher=Memri.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-26}}</ref>

==Counter-conferences==
* In reaction to this conference, a counter-conference on anti-Semitism and Holocaust denial was organised in Berlin<ref name=reimann>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/0,1518,453691,00.html|title=Berlin Counters Holocaust Conference|first=Anna|last=Reimann|publisher=Der Spiegel|date=2006-12-11|accessdate=2006-12-12}}</ref> entitled "The Holocaust in Transnational Memory." The keynote speaker was American Holocaust historian [[Raul Hilberg]], author of "[[The Destruction of the European Jews]]."<ref name=counter>{{cite web|title=Yad Vashem and Germany organize counter-conferences|url=http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/800230.html|date=2006-12-13|accessdate=2006-12-16}}</ref> Topics discussed included the mechanisms and intentions  at the root of the various forms of Holocaust denial and the polarization of the Muslim and Western worlds.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Holocaust in Transnational Memory|url=http://www.bpb.de/files/NN75Y0.pdf|accessdate=2006-12-16|format=PDF}}</ref> According to the ''[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]]'', "speakers emphasized that Holocaust denial is a form of anti-Semitism and that Ahmadinejad is using the theme, together with his threats against Israel, to gain international standing among Arabs." Israeli scholar David Menashri stated that a "silent majority" of Iranians would reject Ahmadinejad's Holocaust denial.<ref>{{cite web|title=Decrying Holocaust denial parley in Iran|url=http://www.clevelandjewishnews.com/articles/2006/12/14/news/world/aaxelrod1215.txt|date=2006-12-12|accessdate=2006-12-16}}</ref> Holocaust historians attending this conference in [[Berlin]] called the Iranian conference "an attempt to cloak [[antisemitism]] in scholarly language."<ref name="Barnard"/>
* A symposium was also held in Jerusalem, entitled, "Holocaust Denial: Paving the Way to Genocide," for members of the diplomatic corps. Its scientific adviser, [[Yehuda Bauer]], said Iran's Holocaust denial was raising objections among Arab intellectuals.<ref name=counter/> Speakers included American Ambassador to the U.N. [[John R. Bolton|John Bolton]]; former Israeli Ambassador to the U.N. [[Dore Gold]]; Israel's Ambassador to the United States [[Meir Roseanne]]; [[Canadian Parliament]] member [[Irwin Cotler]]; and [[Harvard University]] professor [[Alan Dershowitz]]. One proposal was entitled, "Bring Ahmadinejad to Justice For Incitement to Genocide."<ref>{{cite web|title=Take Ahmadinejad Seriously, Bolton Urges |url=http://www.cnsnews.com/ViewNation.asp?Page=/Nation/archive/200612/NAT20061215b.html |date=2006-12-15 |accessdate=2006-12-16 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061218201242/http://www.cnsnews.com/ViewNation.asp?Page=%2FNation%2Farchive%2F200612%2FNAT20061215b.html |archivedate=2006-12-18 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> Speaking at the symposium, [[Yigal Carmon]] of the [[Middle East Media Research Institute]] said "the Iranian regime's Holocaust denial is not a manifestation of irrational hatred, but a premeditated and cold-blooded instrument to achieve its goals [of the] denial of Israel's legitimacy [and the] elimination of the Zionist Entity, i.e. Israel."<ref>{{cite web|title=The Role of Holocaust Denial in the Ideology and Strategy of The Iranian Government|url=http://memri.org/bin/articles.cgi?Page=archives&Area=ia&ID=IA30706|date=2006-12-15|accessdate=2006-12-16}}</ref>
*The [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]] in [[Los Angeles]] planned to hold a teleconference during the same period as the Iranian conference which would focus on individual stories from [[list of Holocaust survivors|Holocaust survivors]].<ref name=reimann/>
* The [[Bali Holocaust Conference]] was held in June 2007 in [[Bali]], [[Indonesia]]. The conference aimed to promote [[religious toleration|religious tolerance]] and affirm the reality of [[the Holocaust]] and was attended by rabbis, Holocaust witnesses, and Muslim leaders, teachers and students. This event was convened by former [[President of Indonesia|Indonesian president]] [[Abdurrahman Wahid]], and was sponsored by the [[Wahid Institute]], the Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los Angeles, and the Libforall Foundation. Wahid stated that although he is a good friend of [[Iran]]ian [[President of Iran|President]] [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]], Ahmadinejad's views about the Holocaust are wrong and constitute "falsified history", and that the Holocaust really happened.<ref>Robin McDowell, [http://legacy.signonsandiego.com/news/world/20070612-0641-indonesia-battlingextremism.html "Jewish Holocaust survivor appeals for tolerance at conference in Muslim Indonesia"],''[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]'' (''[[Associated Press]]''), June 12, 2007.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libforall.org/news-bali-AFP.html |title=LibForAll Foundation - Holocaust-affirming conference opens in Indonesia |publisher=Libforall.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-26}}</ref>

